{
  "_comment": "MIPS 5-stage pipeline with full L1 + L2 cache hierarchy and a real write-back policy. Front-end is identical to the standard MIPS demo (HDU + FWD + IF/ID flush); the path between pipe_exmem and pipe_memwb is now: pipe_exmem → L1 (4 lines, direct, write-through) → L2 (8 lines, fully-associative, write-back) → RAM. The 36-instruction unrolled program walks through three STORE+LOAD pairs to addresses 7, 3, and 11. Notably 7 & 3 = 11 & 3 = 3 & 3 = 3, so all three addresses map to the same direct-mapped L1 line — every fresh STORE conflicts with the previous one and evicts it. The LOAD that immediately follows each STORE always HITS in L1 (just written). Final register state: R3=99 (mem[7] read-back), R6=50 (mem[3] read-back), R9=25 (mem[11] read-back). L1 reports 3 misses + 3 hits; L2 reports 3 misses (write-through pushes every store down) and holds all 3 dirty lines; RAM stays empty because the write-back L2 has not yet evicted anything. Open the Pipeline panel CACHE (LIVE) to watch each stage live.",
